    "analysis": "We have completed metric-, trace-, and log-level P95 anomaly scans for the incident window. Summary of what we know so far: metrics show a near-simultaneous elevation across many KPIs starting at 2021-03-12 20:30:00+08:00 affecting many components (Mysql, Redis, Tomcat, IG/MG, apache). Trace anomalies concentrate on MG01/MG02 (many trace pairs with anomalies beginning ~20:32–20:33+08:00) and show IG01→Tomcat* and MG↔docker* pairs with anomalies at various times in the window. Log analysis shows widespread log.error_count “anomalies” at 20:30+08:00 for Tomcat and apache, but these are likely unhelpful because p95=0 so every nonzero or even zero value can be flagged; more meaningful log spikes are in log.row_count and log.gc_pause_max with isolated spikes later (~20:33–20:53+08:00). Taken together: (1) a system-wide metric elevation starts at 20:30+08:00, (2) traces show service-level issues concentrated at MG01/MG02 beginning slightly later (~20:32+08:00), and (3) Tomcat logs show pervasive error_count activity at 20:30 but threshold artifacts reduce confidence. To localize the root cause component we must identify the most-downstream faulty service in trace call chains among the components flagged by metrics (Tomcat*, Mysql*, Redis*, IG/MG, apache*). The next step is to enumerate trace pairs that call into those candidate downstream services (to_Tomcat*, to_Mysql*, to_Redis*, to_apache*) that had P95 anomalies in the window, sorted by earliest anomaly time, so we can see which downstream service first showed trace-level degradation.",
