    "instruction": "From trace_window (trace-level P95-window results), extract all trace pairs where trace_name indicates a call to a candidate service: any trace_name containing 'to_Tomcat', 'to_Mysql', 'to_Redis', or 'to_apache', and where anomaly_count_p95 > 0. Return a compact table sorted by earliest_anomaly_ts_p95 ascending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, points_in_window, anomaly_count_p95, earliest_anomaly_ts_p95. Limit to the first 50 rows. Also return a single integer: number of distinct callee services referenced in these trace_name values (e.g., count distinct target names like Tomcat01, Mysql01, etc.). Keep outputs compact and do not print full raw time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have run a full threshold-based scan across metrics, traces, and logs. Key findings so far: (1) A near-simultaneous, system-wide elevation of many metric KPIs was observed beginning at 2021-03-12 20:30:00+08:00 affecting Mysql, Redis, Tomcat, IG/MG, apache, etc. (2) Trace anomalies concentrate on MG01/MG02 and on IG→Tomcat call pairs; calls to Tomcat services show P95 breaches starting ~20:32–20:34+08:00. (3) Log analysis shows Tomcat and apache log.error_count flagged at 20:30+08:00, but those are suspect because their p95=0; more meaningful log spikes appear in log.row_count and log.gc_pause_max later in the window. Combining evidence: many Tomcat instances show both metric and log anomalies and are targets of trace anomalies from IG components; traces also show MG nodes with many trace anomalies. According to the localization rules, when multiple services at the same level appear faulty, the root cause is usually the most downstream faulty service in trace call chains. We need to check whether Tomcat instances themselves call downstream services (Mysql/Redis) that became faulty earlier, or whether Tomcat instances are the last faulty services in traces. Concretely, we must inspect trace pairs that indicate calls from Tomcat to DB/cache or trace.self for Tomcat/Mysql/Redis to determine which component first shows trace-side degradation and which is most downstream faulty.\n\nWhat can be derived now: Tomcat instances are strong candidates (metrics + logs + being callees of IG). However, MG nodes show many trace anomalies slightly earlier (~20:32). We must check trace pairs that represent calls originating from Tomcat to Mysql/Redis (or trace.self for Mysql/Redis/Tomcat) to see whether DB or cache show earlier or deeper anomalies than Tomcat. This will let us decide whether the root cause is Tomcat (downstream faulty) or Mysql/Redis (downstream faulty), or infra-level (MG/IG).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the already computed trace_window table, extract rows matching any of these conditions: (a) cmdb_id in [Tomcat01,Tomcat02,Tomcat03,Tomcat04] and trace_name contains 'trace.self' or 'trace.from_' or 'trace.to_' (i.e., all trace features for Tomcat services), (b) trace_name contains 'to_Mysql' or 'to_Redis' (any cmdb_id), or (c) cmdb_id in [Mysql01,Mysql02,Redis01,Redis02] and trace_name contains 'trace.self' or 'trace.from_' or 'trace.to_'. Filter to entries with anomaly_count_p95 > 0. Return a compact table sorted by earliest_anomaly_ts_p95 ascending with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, points_in_window, anomaly_count_p95, earliest_anomaly_ts_p95. Limit to top 30 rows. Also return two integers: (1) number of distinct Tomcat instances that have any trace-window anomaly (anomaly_count_p95>0) in this selection, and (2) number of distinct DB/cache instances (Mysql/Redis) that have any trace-window anomaly. Keep outputs compact and store the result in a kernel variable named trace_tomcat_db_window."
}

{
    "analysis": "We filtered trace anomalies focusing on Tomcat and DB/cache. The results show: all four Tomcat instances (Tomcat01–04) have trace-level anomalies within the incident window, with some Tomcat trace.self/from_root entries showing earliest anomalies at 20:30:00+08:00. In contrast, no Mysql/Redis instances appeared in that filtered trace set (num_dbcache_instances_with_anomaly = 0). Combined with earlier findings: (1) metrics show a near-simultaneous many-component P95 breach beginning at 20:30+08:00; (2) logs show widespread log.error_count flags at 20:30+08:00 for Tomcat/apache but p95=0 (artifact) while more meaningful log spikes (row_count, gc_pause_max) occur later; (3) traces show MG01/MG02 with substantial trace anomalies around 20:32–20:33+08:00, and IG→Tomcat call pairs with anomalies starting ~20:32–20:34+08:00, while some Tomcat self/from_root anomalies begin at 20:30+08:00. From the localization rules: when multiple service-level components are faulty, the root cause is typically the most downstream faulty service in traces. Here, Tomcat instances are faulty (trace anomalies, logs, metrics) and appear to be downstream callees of IG; DB/cache do not show earlier faults. This strongly points to Tomcat-level faults beginning at ~20:30+08:00 rather than DB/Redis. To confirm which Tomcat instance(s) are root cause and the precise occurrence time and reason (e.g., high JVM CPU, OOM, GC pause), we must examine Tomcat-specific metric KPIs (JVM CPU, JVM memory, GC pause, system CPU/memory) for consecutive anomalies and earliest breach times.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From metrics_window (per-(cmdb_id,kpi_name) windowed anomaly results), filter to cmdb_id in [Tomcat01,Tomcat02,Tomcat03,Tomcat04]. Produce a compact table (limit 50 rows) sorted by anomaly_count_p95 descending with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, total_count, p95, p90, points_in_window, anomaly_count_p95, earliest_anomaly_ts_p95. Also return two integers: (1) number of distinct Tomcat KPI pairs that had anomaly_count_p95>0, and (2) the earliest earliest_anomaly_ts_p95 among all Tomcat KPI pairs (the earliest Tomcat metric anomaly time). Keep output compact and store the result in a kernel variable named tomcat_metric_anomalies."
}

